---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Types of Hospital Bill Negotiations | hospitalbillnegotiationcalc.com';
const description = 'Overview of hospital bill negotiation approaches: charity care, prompt-pay discounts, billing error corrections, and balance billing disputes.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Types of Hospital Bill Negotiations</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>Charity care / financial assistance</h2><p>Most nonprofit hospitals have financial assistance programs required by the ACA. Apply with income documentation. Can reduce or eliminate the bill entirely for qualifying patients.</p>
  <h2>Self-pay / uninsured discount</h2><p>Hospitals often have a published &ldquo;self-pay rate&rdquo; (typically 60–80% of chargemaster) available to uninsured patients who ask. This is separate from charity care and does not require income documentation.</p>
  <h2>Prompt-pay discount</h2><p>Paying in full quickly (within 30 days) often triggers a 10–30% discount. Ask the billing department directly. Works best for mid-income patients who can pay a lump sum.</p>
  <h2>Billing error correction</h2><p>Request an itemized bill and compare to your Explanation of Benefits (EOB). Challenge duplicate charges, services not rendered, upcoding, and incorrect insurance information. Correcting errors is not negotiation — you are entitled to accurate billing.</p>
  <h2>Balance billing dispute</h2><p>Under the No Surprises Act (effective 2022), surprise medical bills from out-of-network providers for emergency services and certain scheduled care are capped. If you received care at an in-network facility from an out-of-network provider, dispute bills exceeding your in-network cost sharing.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/how-to-negotiate-hospital-bills">how to negotiate hospital bills</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
